The Oklahoman



























MLB: Carl Albert product J.T. Realmuto shared bond with Jose Fernandez

                            by
            
Jacob Unruh 
Published: February 11, 2017  7:32 PM CDT
Updated: February 11, 2017  7:33 PM CDT





0 shares



facebook



twitter



pinterest



email




comments







Advertisement








                    FILE - In this June 7, 2015, file photo, Miami Marlins catcher J.T. Realmuto throws to first base to put out Colorado Rockies first baseman Wilin Rosario in the ninth inning of a baseball game, in Denver. The stolen base has been stolen from much of baseball, an afterthought when spring training starts next week. Sabermetrics have played a huge role in the steal's decline. When a hitter steps into a batter's box and a runner takes a lead, managers and coaches know the pitcher's delivery time to home plate and the catcher's pop time _ the second-plus lag between the ball hitting the mitt and it touching the middle infielder's glove. (AP Photo/David Zalubowski, File)                                    


MIDWEST CITY — The first pitch was impressive enough. A high-90s fastball followed by that electric smile.
The glove popped with a special sound each pitch. It didn't matter the 6-foot-3 right-hander on the mound was roughly 40 pounds overweight.
J.T. Realmuto was amazed.
There stood Jose Fernandez, a teenager at the time full of energy.
“He was just a chubby ol' (19)-year-old kid, but he was throwing gas,” Realmuto said. “He always had that nasty slider. He was by far probably the best pitcher I ever caught stuff-wise.”
Five months after Fernandez's tragic death in a boating accident and just weeks after Royals star Yordano Ventura died in a car accident in the Dominican Republic, baseball returns to work this week.
But there will be heavy hearts.
“It'll definitely be tough the first week or so,” Realmuto told The Oklahoman before it was revealed the Marlins would wear a patch this season to honor Fernandez.
For Realmuto and Fernandez, there was a special bond. The two were considered bright prospects when they met. They quickly became friends, too.
Realmuto was drafted from Carl Albert High School in the third round of the 2010 draft. Then a shortstop who decimated Oklahoma pitching, he was immediately converted to catcher.
With little to no experience behind the plate, he had to learn to call and manage games. He had to learn his pitchers, who in the lower levels make learning to catch challenging with impressive velocity and breaking balls but little to no control.
In 2012 he met Fernandez.
“He was awesome. Just happy as can be; always in a good mood — apart from him being a dominating pitcher,” Realmuto said. “He was just the friendliest kid you'll ever meet. You always knew he was there. He was just one of those guys that you never missed.”
They worked a lot together in Class A. The following spring training they worked even more together with both ticketed to open in Double A.
Fernandez never pitched in the minors that season. He jumped to Miami and ultimately was named Rookie of the Year. Realmuto followed a year later and Fernandez was the lone pitcher on staff Realmuto knew.
And as Realmuto grew behind the plate, he developed an ability to help keep Fernandez out of trouble on the field.
Fernandez's smile and laugh upset opponents following a strikeout. He playfully threw gum at umpires or sunflower seeds at fans. He was loud in the clubhouse.
“He never took anything too serious,” Realmuto said. “It wasn't him trying to show anybody up. It was him legitimately just always having a good time.”
But pitching Fernandez did take seriously. Realmuto noticed something special in the dugout when Fernandez's day was finished.
It's how he wants to remember his friend.
“After a good game you could tell he was just the happiest person on the planet,” Realmuto said.




